{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"57892709-8e44-4355-b6a8-4a466bbc4921","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can give you the guidance you need. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for …</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nKey points:\n\n- **`PackAsTool`** — marks the project as a dotnet tool.\n- **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command users will invoke (e.g., `dotnet tool run my-mcp-server`).\n- **`OutputType`** must be `Exe` (required for tools).\n\nThen pack and publish:\n\n```bash\ndotnet pack -c Release\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key <YOUR_NUGET_API_KEY> \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\nUsers install it with:\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\n```\n\nAnd configure it in their MCP client as:\n\n```json\n{ \"command\": \"my-mcp-server\", \"args\": [], \"transport\": \"stdio\" }\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"de5f9795-bf50-4445-8ff9-6ea4dca8e64a","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"D025:56792:15CE36C:184EA86:6A067438"},"id":"21a4d0a6-4202-42c3-86a1-3b4b45a338ed","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:17:52.246Z","parentId":"c05ce2ce-ce3f-4c38-b194-92b1a1d3d0c8"}
